> Fra diavolo literally means "brother devil" in Italian. When you get a whiff of its fiery heat, you'll understand how it earned its infernal name (you can always deploy the heat-packing ingredients to taste, of course). Centered around a thick tomato sauce and filled out with plump shrimp and al dente linguine, it's got all the features of a classic red-sauce recipe but with the fire turned up a few notches.

Wash and dry all produce. Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Halve, peel, and dice @yellow onion{1}(halved, peeled, and diced). Pick leaves from @oregano{1/4%ounce}. Discard stems and finely chop leaves. Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add garlic, onion, half the oregano, and a pinch of @chili flakes{1%tsp} (to taste). Cook until softened, about ~{5%minutes}, tossing occasionally. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Add @diced tomatoes{1%can} and @sugar{1/2%tsp} to pan. Reduce heat to medium-low and let simmer until thickened, about ~{10%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Once water is boiling, add @linguine{6%ounce} to #pot. Cook until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Drain, reserving 1/4 cup cooking water.

Season @shrimp{10%ounce} with salt and pepper. Add to pan and stir into tomato sauce. Let shrimp cook until pink and completely opaque, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Toss linguine into pan, coating with sauce. Add a splash of cooking water if necessary to give tomatoes a saucy consistency. Season with salt and pepper. Divide linguine and shrimp between plates. Sprinkle with remaining oregano and any additional chili flakes, if desired.